attributes.text: Following the diagnosis of SLE, patients are assessed for disease activity and organ involvement, both of which dictate the most appropriate therapy. SLE patients with a mild involvement can be easily managed with a low dose of oral steroids (to be discontinued as soon as possible), hydroxychloroquine, and symptomatic drugs. Moderate to severe manifestations usually require the addition of DMARDs and immunosuppressants, like methotrexate, mofetil mycophenolate, cyclophosphamide and azathioprine, or the administration of intravenous immunoglobulins. The use of biologic agents (belimumab or rituximab) is indicated in refractory forms of disease. SLE flares are treated with intravenous steroid pulses and prevented with long-term low doses of oral glucocorticoids. In addition, symptomatic or organ-specific drugs, like analgesics, antihypertensive or antiepileptic agents, are often co-prescribed. In case of a concomitant APS diagnosis, anti-thrombotic and anti-coagulant drugs, and, in severe forms, plasma exchange, may also be needed. Darker color in the bars indicates higher doses or a more common use of the referred medications. If you have moderate to severe lupus, you may need to take stronger medicine like methotrexate.

attributes.simplified_text: In the future, scientists will make new drugs that will help people with lupus. These drugs might be used to treat people with lupus who have active glomerulonephritis (kidney inflammation), central nervous system involvement (brain and spinal cord), or high levels of autoantibodies (proteins made by the body that attack its own healthy tissues). Lupus can be hard to treat, and these new drugs could make it easier to treat.

attributes.summary: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) is a disease in which the body's immune system attacks its own tissues, causing inflammation and damage. It mainly affects women during their childbearing years. The cause of SLE is not known. Scientists think that a combination of genetic and environmental factors may trigger the disease.

Some drugs are made up of amino acids. Amino acids are the building blocks of proteins. These drugs are called therapeutic peptides. The drugs target a specific disease, like lupus. The drugs are very specific to their target, and they have low toxicity. They would be the best treatment for lupus, if they were available. However, no therapeutic peptide has been approved for use in lupus patients yet.

People with SLE have antibodies that attack parts of their own bodies. A study was done to see if a drug could stop the antibodies from attacking. The drug was given to 20 people with SLE in Bulgaria. It seemed to work, but the study was not big enough to be sure. Two other studies were done in the US, sponsored by different companies. One study showed that the drug worked, but the other study did not.

CDRs are the parts of antibodies and TCRs that recognize and interact with antigens. Some scientists have done experiments on mice and people, and they found that the heavy chains of anti-dsDNA antibodies can behave as immunogenic epitopes and elicit a T cell response.

For a long time, it was believed that SLE glomerulonephritis could be the result of immune complex deposition, however, recent evidence suggests that it may also derive from the direct interaction of autoantibodies with autoantigens present in the glomerular extracellular matrix [69].

Nucleosomes are the basic building blocks of your DNA. Antibodies in people with lupus react to the basic building blocks of your DNA. A peptide derived from a human and mouse T-cell immunodominant epitope placed within H2A was given to mice with lupus, and it helped them.
Antibodies that cross the blood-brain barrier can cause brain cells to die.
Glatiramer acetate (Teva Pharmaceutical Industries) is a medicine that is made of a mixture of four natural amino acids. It is used to treat multiple sclerosis.
Thymopentin is an artificial version of a hormone that is found in the thymus gland. It has a special sequence of five amino acids, and it helps your body make more white blood cells.

A medicine called AMG623 is a drug that is made to treat a disease called lupus. The medicine is made of four pieces of a protein that binds to BLyS, which is a protein that makes lupus worse. The medicine is made of pieces of a protein that binds to BLyS, and it's attached to the Fc part of an antibody.

Contrary to other drugs, whose effects in SLE have been studied in the lab and in clinical trials, the evidence concerning the effects of AMG531 or romiplostim (Amgen) in SLE comes from real-life experience.
CXCR4 is a protein on the surface of cells that lets certain proteins in the blood attach to it. CXCR4 is found on blood cells, cancer cells, and some other cells.

Due to the impaired clearance of nucleic acids, the endoplasmic reticulum (ER)-resident protein stimulator of interferon genes (STING)-cyclic GMP-AMP synthase (cGAS) pathway is typically hyper-activated in SLE and associated with the type I IFN response [118].

A virus that causes a disease in humans called Torque Teno Virus (TTV) is found in the blood of people with a disease called SLE. The TTV virus is also found in the blood of people who have HIV, but don't have SLE. People with SLE make antibodies that react against the HIV virus. A virus that causes a disease in mice called HERV-H is found in the blood of people with SLE.

In the past, scientists have tried to make drugs that would help people with lupus. They have made many different kinds of drugs, but none of them worked very well. Now, scientists are trying to make new drugs that will help people with lupus. They are trying to make these new drugs by using a special process called "biotechnology". These new drugs are made from special chemicals that come from living things. These new drugs are not like the old ones.
We expect that knowing more about how the disease works will help us to treat it better.

The treatment of SLE still relies on a conservative approach, combining multiple unselective immunosuppressive agents [8] and, consecutively, increasing the risk of unwanted side effects. In this effervescent panorama, therapeutic peptides, able to interfere with the most crucial steps of SLE immunopathogen- esis, may represent an additional intriguing pharmacologic strategy. To date, no therapeutic peptide has been licensed and marketed for the use in SLE patients.
